00:00:12.682 --> 00:00:13.890
ANDREW CYR: Thank you, Alice.

00:00:17.010 --> 00:00:18.240
Good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:19.870
It's an honor to be here.

00:00:19.870 --> 00:00:22.980
I began Metropolis
Ensemble 10 years ago,

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:25.140
in part with a
simple guiding notion

00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:27.510
that the heart of the
classical music tradition

00:00:27.510 --> 00:00:31.350
really embraces and celebrates
exploration and discovery

00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:34.620
and really the search for
new forms of expression.

00:00:34.620 --> 00:00:36.810
You know, the great works
that make up today what

00:00:36.810 --> 00:00:39.840
we call like the
repertoire, the canon

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:43.910
are often the ones that
represent-- for the composers,

00:00:43.910 --> 00:00:45.870
they're kind of like
wildest experiments,

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:51.070
or their most bold sort of
unusual works performed.

00:00:51.070 --> 00:00:55.440
But today we don't often
associate classical music with,

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:59.910
for example, technology or
groundbreaking new things.

00:00:59.910 --> 00:01:02.630
But the instruments that we now
kind of are very traditional,

00:01:02.630 --> 00:01:04.560
like the violin, or
the piano, or even

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:06.930
like the antiquated pipe organ--

00:01:06.930 --> 00:01:08.700
at the time, these
instruments were

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:10.530
kind of really
newfangled inventions

00:01:10.530 --> 00:01:15.420
and were kind of like the Google
of yesterday, so to speak.

00:01:15.420 --> 00:01:17.580
New forms of
tuning, for example,

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:21.510
in Bach's time, and then later
advancements in chromaticism

00:01:21.510 --> 00:01:23.340
with Wagner, for example--

00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:27.690
these things that dazzled
musicians and listeners alike.

00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:31.320
And they presented really
endless forms of variations.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:34.620
Metropolis's first experiments
in music technology

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:36.480
really started in
2008 when we did

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:39.990
a remix of "The Rite of Spring"
with Ricardo Romaneiro, Ryan,

00:01:39.990 --> 00:01:43.540
Francis and engineer Leo Leite,
and we never looked back.

00:01:43.540 --> 00:01:46.110
Today, I'm very
thrilled to present

00:01:46.110 --> 00:01:47.910
another one of our
roster composers

00:01:47.910 --> 00:01:52.740
and close collaborators,
Elliot Cole, whose explorations

00:01:52.740 --> 00:01:55.410
in original software, I
guess I should call it,

00:01:55.410 --> 00:01:59.430
are interwoven with his
beautiful and evolving music

00:01:59.430 --> 00:02:00.462
aesthetic.

00:02:00.462 --> 00:02:02.670
He will be joined by a
handful of Metropolis Ensemble

00:02:02.670 --> 00:02:03.570
musicians--

00:02:03.570 --> 00:02:07.140
Eric Umble on clarinet,
Jordan Dodson on guitar,

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:11.980
Gabe or Gabriel
Cabezas on cello,

00:02:11.980 --> 00:02:14.110
and Andrea Lodge on piano later.

00:02:14.110 --> 00:02:16.599
So thank you so much,
and I hope you enjoy.

00:02:16.599 --> 00:02:19.413
