00:22:19.094 --> 00:22:20.510
But I grew up with
a professional.

00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:22.790
My mom taught herself
to program and ended up

00:22:22.790 --> 00:22:26.900
coding GIS software for the
state of Texas in the '80s.

00:22:26.900 --> 00:22:30.020
And I grew up--

00:22:30.020 --> 00:22:31.150
she taught me HyperCard.

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:32.233
Do you remember HyperCard?

00:22:32.233 --> 00:22:34.340
Did anybody-- yeah.

00:22:34.340 --> 00:22:37.250
So me and her were doing
HyperCard projects together

00:22:37.250 --> 00:22:38.900
when I was like
really a little kid.

00:22:38.900 --> 00:22:43.554
And I chased music, but
I always kind of knew

00:22:43.554 --> 00:22:45.470
in the back of my mind
that this was the thing

00:22:45.470 --> 00:22:48.950
that I could come back to
and figure out on my own

00:22:48.950 --> 00:22:51.840
if I wanted to when I needed to.

00:22:51.840 --> 00:22:54.290
So I picked it up
about seven years ago

00:22:54.290 --> 00:22:58.574
to start this project
that I have shown you now.

00:22:58.574 --> 00:22:59.990
So tell you a
little bit about it.

00:22:59.990 --> 00:23:01.430
It's called "Bloom."

00:23:01.430 --> 00:23:03.920
And I started down the
rabbit hole of this music

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:08.570
because I for
inexplicable reasons

00:23:08.570 --> 00:23:10.580
was fantasizing
listening to a music that

00:23:10.580 --> 00:23:13.305
just sounded like this.

00:23:13.305 --> 00:23:27.674
[MUSIC - ELLIOT COLE, "BLOOM"]

00:23:27.674 --> 00:23:29.340
So I first started
trying to write music

00:23:29.340 --> 00:23:31.770
like this at a piano.

00:23:31.770 --> 00:23:33.750
I would lock myself in
a practice room, piece

00:23:33.750 --> 00:23:36.720
of paper, pencil,
and I thought that it

00:23:36.720 --> 00:23:39.360
would be kind of easy,
because all I wanted to hear

00:23:39.360 --> 00:23:41.250
was random notes.

00:23:41.250 --> 00:23:43.740
And you'd think it would be
easy to sit down and write

00:23:43.740 --> 00:23:45.570
random notes.

00:23:45.570 --> 00:23:49.140
Turns out it's really hard
to try to not make choices.

00:23:49.140 --> 00:23:51.720
As soon as you're there
feeling every little thing,

00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:55.020
you start to care about this
pull and this push, and are

00:23:55.020 --> 00:23:56.340
these two things attracted?

00:23:56.340 --> 00:23:57.600
Are they too much attracted?

00:23:57.600 --> 00:23:59.870
Do we have to thwart them
with exactly the right note

00:23:59.870 --> 00:24:01.542
at exactly the right time?

00:24:01.542 --> 00:24:03.000
You can kind of
make yourself crazy

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:06.720
trying to make the perfect
thing when actually there's not

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:09.660
really a perfect thing to find?

00:24:09.660 --> 00:24:12.660
This is what I started
to suspect as I

00:24:12.660 --> 00:24:15.750
was trying to do it this way.

00:24:15.750 --> 00:24:20.430
I like to think about art as
a dialogue between expression

00:24:20.430 --> 00:24:21.810
and discovery.

00:24:21.810 --> 00:24:24.420
Expression pulls something
out of us that's inside of us.

00:24:24.420 --> 00:24:28.080
Discovery is something outside
of us that we bring in.

00:24:28.080 --> 00:24:31.110
And I think when I was
trying to write this at first

00:24:31.110 --> 00:24:34.290
at the piano I was trying to
express something of myself

00:24:34.290 --> 00:24:34.980
in it.

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:37.800
I was trying to choose exactly
the right notes that only

00:24:37.800 --> 00:24:39.850
I would choose.

00:24:39.850 --> 00:24:43.025
But I-- really this was
the wrong path for me,

00:24:43.025 --> 00:24:44.400
I think, because
it really needed

00:24:44.400 --> 00:24:45.960
to be a music of discovery.

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:49.530
I really wanted to be able to
go out and find these things

00:24:49.530 --> 00:24:51.960
and then make choices,
then care about them,

00:24:51.960 --> 00:24:53.970
then figure out
which ones I liked.

00:24:53.970 --> 00:25:00.000
So my mental image here is of
a garden, of a wild overgrown

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:00.720
garden.

00:25:00.720 --> 00:25:04.740
And each plant is a little
constellation of notes.

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:07.260
And my job--

00:25:07.260 --> 00:25:10.760
I was commuting on New Jersey
Transit like three hours a day

00:25:10.760 --> 00:25:11.760
in this time in my life.

00:25:11.760 --> 00:25:13.440
And I dreamed of just
being able to sit

00:25:13.440 --> 00:25:15.570
with my eyes closed and
my computer half-shut

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:20.550
and just listen to bloom
after bloom after bloom

00:25:20.550 --> 00:25:23.340
from this garden,
explore it with my ears,

00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:26.070
and pick things that
I like and shape them

00:25:26.070 --> 00:25:28.600
and transplant them and
make them a little softer

00:25:28.600 --> 00:25:31.132
and make them a little fuller,
spin them around, try them

00:25:31.132 --> 00:25:33.090
out different ways, and
make some kind of music

00:25:33.090 --> 00:25:38.190
of subtle variations
of what I think

00:25:38.190 --> 00:25:42.060
are kind of infinitely
beautiful, simple, random sets

00:25:42.060 --> 00:25:44.940
of events.

00:25:44.940 --> 00:25:48.197
So I wanted to do--

00:25:48.197 --> 00:25:50.530
I thought a computer would
be a good way to approach it.

00:25:50.530 --> 00:25:51.300
I thought of my mom.

00:25:51.300 --> 00:25:52.920
I thought my mom would
say, just write a program.

00:25:52.920 --> 00:25:53.800
You can do it.

00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:56.186
So I started learning this
programming language called

00:25:56.186 --> 00:25:57.810
SuperCollider, which
a lot of musicians

00:25:57.810 --> 00:26:01.470
use because it's got
a synthesizer built in

00:26:01.470 --> 00:26:04.620
and started trying to
represent my blooms.

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:08.040
So you'll see that
it's a class that

00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:10.630
is really just three lists.

00:26:10.630 --> 00:26:13.072
There's a list of notes,
a list of velocities--

00:26:13.072 --> 00:26:14.280
it's a little confusing here.

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:16.185
Velocity here means
volume, basically.

00:26:16.185 --> 00:26:19.350
It's how fast you play the key--

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:20.460
and time intervals.

00:26:20.460 --> 00:26:23.850
This is how much time
is in between each note.

00:26:23.850 --> 00:26:26.905
And then I wrote a
whole library of--

00:26:26.905 --> 00:26:28.530
that's probably not
the technical word.

00:26:28.530 --> 00:26:31.020
I wrote a whole bunch of
methods for this class

00:26:31.020 --> 00:26:33.100
that you've seen
a bunch of already

00:26:33.100 --> 00:26:37.020
for manipulating those
lists, basically.

00:26:37.020 --> 00:26:39.300
And then I started
figuring out ways

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:43.440
to write patterns that
would read out these lists,

00:26:43.440 --> 00:26:46.200
spinning infinitely
in every direction,

00:26:46.200 --> 00:26:47.779
like you've also heard some of.

00:26:47.779 --> 00:26:49.320
Those are the
experiments that turned

00:26:49.320 --> 00:26:51.210
into a couple of
these pieces that I'm

00:26:51.210 --> 00:26:52.215
sharing with you today.

00:26:55.470 --> 00:26:58.010
So I just have a couple
of reflections of things

00:26:58.010 --> 00:27:01.160
that I've learned about, and
then we'll hear some more music

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:03.320
on the piano.

00:27:03.320 --> 00:27:05.060
So I've learned
a lot about music

00:27:05.060 --> 00:27:07.790
from listening to a lot of
these random sets of notes.

00:27:07.790 --> 00:27:11.490
And I think there are
three main things.

00:27:11.490 --> 00:27:13.352
One is that making sense--

00:27:13.352 --> 00:27:15.560
this feeling that we have
that something that we hear

00:27:15.560 --> 00:27:16.469
makes sense--

00:27:16.469 --> 00:27:17.510
what does that even mean?

00:27:17.510 --> 00:27:19.520
Like, it's something
that we know,

00:27:19.520 --> 00:27:21.350
but it's very hard to quantify.

00:27:21.350 --> 00:27:23.420
I think it's about
making simple shapes

00:27:23.420 --> 00:27:26.090
and being able to
perceive simple shapes.

00:27:26.090 --> 00:27:28.100
So check it out each
of these blooms.

00:27:28.100 --> 00:27:31.537
[MUSIC - ELLIOT COLE, "BLOOM"]

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:38.540
I don't know.

00:27:38.540 --> 00:27:42.050
To me, they all kind of make
sense as musical gestures.

00:27:42.050 --> 00:27:46.400
They make sense because there's
actually one dimension of them

00:27:46.400 --> 00:27:48.050
that is in a simple shape.

00:27:48.050 --> 00:27:52.430
So it's random notes,
random time intervals.

00:27:55.244 --> 00:27:56.660
I better show it
to you let's see.

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:03.600
So random notes,
random velocities,

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:05.970
random time intervals,
but the velocities

00:28:05.970 --> 00:28:08.850
are sorted largest to smallest.

00:28:08.850 --> 00:28:11.370
So they start loud, and
then they get quieter.

00:28:11.370 --> 00:28:14.220
And just by applying
this one envelope,

00:28:14.220 --> 00:28:18.450
this one shape, across whatever
random materials is in there,

00:28:18.450 --> 00:28:20.550
creates a gesture
that makes sense.

00:28:20.550 --> 00:28:21.790
It feels like a single thing.

00:28:21.790 --> 00:28:23.845
It feels like a whole.

00:28:23.845 --> 00:28:26.220
So that's the first thing I
learned making sense in music

00:28:26.220 --> 00:28:29.100
is about making simple
shapes in some dimension.

00:28:32.040 --> 00:28:36.000
Second thing is that not every
dimension needs to make sense.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:37.740
If you can make one dimension--

00:28:37.740 --> 00:28:41.400
volume or pitch or
rhythm or timbre--

00:28:41.400 --> 00:28:44.250
make a lot of sense, then
you get a lot of freedom

00:28:44.250 --> 00:28:49.800
to let the other
things not make sense.

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:51.920
So those are the two
things that, even when

00:28:51.920 --> 00:28:55.190
I'm not making music
with the computer,

00:28:55.190 --> 00:28:58.760
I'm thinking about as
I'm making music now.

00:28:58.760 --> 00:29:02.660
And then the last thing is
that memory is everything.

00:29:02.660 --> 00:29:06.020
Whether or not we've heard the
sound before or not is actually

00:29:06.020 --> 00:29:09.320
maybe the most salient flavor
compared to the content

00:29:09.320 --> 00:29:11.570
of what's actually in there.

00:29:11.570 --> 00:29:12.740
So let's do an experiment.

00:29:12.740 --> 00:29:14.960
I'm going to play the
same line three times,

00:29:14.960 --> 00:29:19.250
and I just want you to check
in with the experience of how

00:29:19.250 --> 00:29:21.500
the first one feels
different from the third one.

00:29:21.500 --> 00:29:42.460
[MUSIC - ELLIOT COLE, "BLOOM"]

00:29:42.460 --> 00:29:44.520
A traditional musical
analysis would say, oh,

00:29:44.520 --> 00:29:47.610
it's three identical
sets of pitches.

00:29:47.610 --> 00:29:50.490
But the experience of them
is so different, right?

00:29:50.490 --> 00:29:51.910
The first one is baffling.

00:29:51.910 --> 00:29:54.600
And the third one is
like pretty satisfying--

00:29:54.600 --> 00:29:56.760
to hear it exactly
the same way with all

00:29:56.760 --> 00:29:59.770
of the subtle variation.

00:29:59.770 --> 00:30:03.930
So I think that this is
why sitting at the piano

00:30:03.930 --> 00:30:08.380
and trying to write this was
a little bit crazy-making.

00:30:08.380 --> 00:30:10.860
There's no right or
wrong note to choose.

00:30:10.860 --> 00:30:12.930
Notes don't matter
in themselves.

00:30:12.930 --> 00:30:15.810
They come to matter through
repetition and familiarity

00:30:15.810 --> 00:30:18.930
and having a relationship
with your memory.

00:30:18.930 --> 00:30:22.590
So those are the things that
I've learned doing this.

00:30:22.590 --> 00:30:26.550
And I'd like to share a little
bit more music with you.

00:30:26.550 --> 00:30:29.545
I think because of time,
let's just do the nocturne.

00:30:29.545 --> 00:30:30.330
Is that all right?

00:30:30.330 --> 00:30:30.830
Great.

00:30:35.530 --> 00:30:37.530
I'm going to do a
little intro, actually.

