00:37:23.520 --> 00:37:29.340
ELLIOT COLE: Yeah, yeah,
most of the software that's

00:37:29.340 --> 00:37:33.020
kind of commercially
available to make music

00:37:33.020 --> 00:37:34.680
is to make music easier, right?

00:37:34.680 --> 00:37:40.680
So it's like designed to be
recorded, played in, maybe

00:37:40.680 --> 00:37:42.240
clicked in, and
kind of composed.

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:50.940
But none of them let me
write an abstract pattern

00:37:50.940 --> 00:37:52.950
irrespective of the
pitches that are

00:37:52.950 --> 00:37:54.340
going to be in it, for example.

00:37:54.340 --> 00:37:56.548
That's something that I
really want to be able to do.

00:37:56.548 --> 00:37:59.670
I want to be able to
say, I want a series of--

00:37:59.670 --> 00:38:02.490
I want this rhythmic pattern
to happen this many times.

00:38:02.490 --> 00:38:04.860
I don't care what
the notes are yet.

00:38:04.860 --> 00:38:07.230
And so being able to work
on that level of abstraction

00:38:07.230 --> 00:38:11.760
is just not something that
Ableton or Fruity Loops

00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:14.910
or Logic are designed to do.

00:38:14.910 --> 00:38:19.470
So I like thinking about
this as music the hard way.

00:38:19.470 --> 00:38:21.520
It's like a little
dumb to do it this way.

00:38:21.520 --> 00:38:24.300
Sometimes I'll spend a lot of
time doing something this way

00:38:24.300 --> 00:38:27.540
that I could have done
a much simpler way.

00:38:27.540 --> 00:38:33.680
But certain things are
possible also through it.

00:38:33.680 --> 00:38:36.390
AUDIENCE: Is this the primary
way that you create music?

00:38:36.390 --> 00:38:38.170
ELLIOT COLE: Maybe like 33%.

00:38:40.980 --> 00:38:43.950
Yeah, but it shaped my
thinking much bigger than that,

00:38:43.950 --> 00:38:47.107
I think, in a couple of
the ways that I described.

00:38:47.107 --> 00:38:47.940
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:49.482
ELLIOT COLE: Thank you.

00:38:49.482 --> 00:38:50.029
Hi.

00:38:50.029 --> 00:38:52.070
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming
and performing today.

00:38:52.070 --> 00:38:53.486
ELLIOT COLE: Thanks
for having me.

00:38:53.486 --> 00:38:58.200
AUDIENCE: So when you want
to have a musician play this,

00:38:58.200 --> 00:39:01.181
do you have to do some
tweaking for the instruments?

00:39:01.181 --> 00:39:02.430
ELLIOT COLE: Yeah, definitely.

00:39:02.430 --> 00:39:06.870
So not all things are
possible on all instruments,

00:39:06.870 --> 00:39:11.940
and so I have to have a pretty
good idea of the end goal.

00:39:11.940 --> 00:39:15.780
One, when I'm thinking about
the patterns in the first place,

00:39:15.780 --> 00:39:17.790
it's worth considering
what ultimately

00:39:17.790 --> 00:39:19.700
is going to be playing this.

00:39:19.700 --> 00:39:23.210
But also, then,
there's a stage--

00:39:23.210 --> 00:39:26.190
you know I can spin out
stuff all day, and some of it

00:39:26.190 --> 00:39:27.430
I get really excited about.

00:39:27.430 --> 00:39:28.350
And I record it all.

00:39:28.350 --> 00:39:31.260
But then there's the process
of turning it into a score.

00:39:31.260 --> 00:39:34.860
And in the process of
transcribing, turning it

00:39:34.860 --> 00:39:36.180
into notes on a page--

00:39:36.180 --> 00:39:39.210
a whole lot of
editorializing opportunity.

00:39:39.210 --> 00:39:41.197
It's hard not to make choices.

00:39:41.197 --> 00:39:43.530
And then I started cutting
stuff, making things perfect,

00:39:43.530 --> 00:39:45.540
fixing notes.

00:39:45.540 --> 00:39:47.430
So there's a lot
of composition that

00:39:47.430 --> 00:39:51.930
happens after this
initial burst of stuff.

00:39:51.930 --> 00:39:55.160
And in that stage adapting
things to the instrument

00:39:55.160 --> 00:39:57.784
is just something I do
on a note-but-note basis.

00:39:57.784 --> 00:39:59.450
AUDIENCE: So you do
that manually, then?

00:39:59.450 --> 00:40:03.280
ELLIOT COLE:
Super-manually, yeah.

00:40:03.280 --> 00:40:08.032
It would be a fun project to
try to write the program that

00:40:08.032 --> 00:40:09.490
filters out the
notes that couldn't

00:40:09.490 --> 00:40:12.160
be done at the same time
on the guitar or something.

00:40:12.160 --> 00:40:14.080
But honestly it would
take me three months,

00:40:14.080 --> 00:40:17.131
and I might as well just do it.

00:40:17.131 --> 00:40:19.630
AUDIENCE: First off, let me say
that was absolutely amazing.

00:40:19.630 --> 00:40:20.230
ELLIOT COLE: Oh, thank you.

00:40:20.230 --> 00:40:21.469
AUDIENCE: Thanks for that.

00:40:21.469 --> 00:40:23.635
And then, I'm interested
in the aspect of licensing.

00:40:23.635 --> 00:40:27.160
We know with software licenses,
we know with music licenses,

00:40:27.160 --> 00:40:29.510
I am not sure if
that bloom class is

00:40:29.510 --> 00:40:34.670
music, is an instrument, but
have you considered licensing?

00:40:34.670 --> 00:40:37.240
ELLIOT COLE: It's written
amateurishly enough

00:40:37.240 --> 00:40:41.200
that I think it would be maybe
a little frustrating for anyone

00:40:41.200 --> 00:40:44.440
other than me to learn to use.

00:40:44.440 --> 00:40:47.200
But it's written
in SuperCollider,

00:40:47.200 --> 00:40:50.084
which is open source,
and so downstream it

00:40:50.084 --> 00:40:51.250
needs to be open source too.

00:40:51.250 --> 00:40:56.050
So I'm not in a position to
try to control what people

00:40:56.050 --> 00:40:58.510
do with it or something,
if I'm thinking

00:40:58.510 --> 00:40:59.680
of licensing the right way.

00:40:59.680 --> 00:41:03.140
But I'd be happy to share it.

00:41:03.140 --> 00:41:05.399
But it's a little quirky
and personal at the moment.

00:41:05.399 --> 00:41:07.690
AUDIENCE: I'm sure I'm not
the only one in the room who

00:41:07.690 --> 00:41:08.260
wants to play with it.

00:41:08.260 --> 00:41:09.190
ELLIOT COLE: Oh, you
want to play with it.

00:41:09.190 --> 00:41:09.870
OK, that's--

00:41:09.870 --> 00:41:10.490
AUDIENCE: Links to anywhere?

00:41:10.490 --> 00:41:12.850
Do you have a GitHub repo
somewhere we can look at it?

00:41:12.850 --> 00:41:15.130
ELLIOT COLE: No, I learned
how to do that once,

00:41:15.130 --> 00:41:18.200
and then I didn't
do it ever again.

00:41:18.200 --> 00:41:21.010
So let me put my email
address right here.

00:41:21.010 --> 00:41:23.539
I'd love to be in touch with
anyone who wants to geek out

00:41:23.539 --> 00:41:24.580
about this stuff with me.

00:41:28.190 --> 00:41:30.040
And I'd be happy
to share the code.

00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:32.050
And it would probably
be a good project

00:41:32.050 --> 00:41:34.790
to kind of get it cleaned up and
write a little documentation.

00:41:34.790 --> 00:41:35.470
AUDIENCE: Thanks so much.

00:41:35.470 --> 00:41:36.761
ELLIOT COLE: Thanks for asking.

00:41:40.916 --> 00:41:42.790
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
if you can describe

00:41:42.790 --> 00:41:45.110
for this specific
piece, just for fun,

00:41:45.110 --> 00:41:47.736
the nocturne-- can you describe
the process of how you composed

00:41:47.736 --> 00:41:48.235
it?

00:41:48.235 --> 00:41:49.690
ELLIOT COLE: Yeah
well, so that's

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:56.200
one where the idea came
from playing around in code,

00:41:56.200 --> 00:42:01.230
but then the
composition happened

00:42:01.230 --> 00:42:02.620
in a much more traditional way.

00:42:02.620 --> 00:42:04.680
So what I discovered
that I loved

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:08.520
is if you take a set of notes
that have different time

00:42:08.520 --> 00:42:11.010
intervals between them
and different loudnesses

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:14.550
of each one, and then you just
double each entry, or triple

00:42:14.550 --> 00:42:19.470
each entry, it's pretty magical
to hear three identical notes

00:42:19.470 --> 00:42:23.370
with identical times in between
them, and then turn on a dime

00:42:23.370 --> 00:42:27.300
to another set of four that are
really different, but also all

00:42:27.300 --> 00:42:28.540
identical.

00:42:28.540 --> 00:42:30.840
And so that was what
I discovered I liked

00:42:30.840 --> 00:42:33.110
by just manipulating lists.

00:42:33.110 --> 00:42:36.330
And then when it came to
writing this piece of music,

00:42:36.330 --> 00:42:42.890
I kind of knew what I wanted
the motion in the melody to be

00:42:42.890 --> 00:42:47.340
and then composed it at a piano,
feeling all the right notes

00:42:47.340 --> 00:42:51.610
that I wanted to make, writing
this kind of linear bass

00:42:51.610 --> 00:42:53.340
line moving.

00:42:53.340 --> 00:42:56.850
So that's all kind of free
composed in the usual way.

00:42:57.510 --> 00:42:59.350
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:42:59.350 --> 00:43:02.360
So this instrument opens
a lot of possibilities.

00:43:02.360 --> 00:43:06.450
I was wondering if compared
to more traditional

00:43:06.450 --> 00:43:09.450
musical creation you
sometimes feel lost,

00:43:09.450 --> 00:43:11.652
because you have
so many options?

00:43:11.652 --> 00:43:12.360
ELLIOT COLE: Yes.

00:43:12.360 --> 00:43:13.210
All the time.

00:43:13.210 --> 00:43:17.250
Yeah, I feel very
lost, especially

00:43:17.250 --> 00:43:22.890
given that there aren't a
lot of points of intersection

00:43:22.890 --> 00:43:25.560
with the rest of the world
where it sort of makes sense

00:43:25.560 --> 00:43:26.580
to anybody else.

00:43:26.580 --> 00:43:32.230
So yeah, I mean I've
been challenging myself.

00:43:32.230 --> 00:43:36.870
I'm part of a tradition of
music education and values

00:43:36.870 --> 00:43:42.720
that is about challenging
itself to be a little lost

00:43:42.720 --> 00:43:46.920
and find your own personal
way to put notes together.

00:43:46.920 --> 00:43:59.220
And not having models
I guess let's me--

00:43:59.220 --> 00:44:03.630
I don't know-- it's a loss that
makes me kind of confident,

00:44:03.630 --> 00:44:06.990
because it's kind of just
between me and me, you know?

00:44:06.990 --> 00:44:10.210
I don't know what
I need to do next.

00:44:10.210 --> 00:44:13.920
But I have a way to dig in and
find something that excites me.

00:44:13.920 --> 00:44:17.050
And I think that's
what it's for.

00:44:20.890 --> 00:44:22.810
Yes.

00:44:22.810 --> 00:44:26.210
AUDIENCE: So here you've got
notes, velocities, and time

00:44:26.210 --> 00:44:28.690
intervals to represent a sound.

00:44:28.690 --> 00:44:31.990
How easy or hard is that
to transcribe to something

00:44:31.990 --> 00:44:35.020
with multiple instruments, like
the first piece that you did?

00:44:35.020 --> 00:44:39.190
ELLIOT COLE: Yeah, that just
brings in my other skills

00:44:39.190 --> 00:44:39.880
as a composer.

00:44:39.880 --> 00:44:43.600
So I may use this to generate
some big swath of material

00:44:43.600 --> 00:44:48.970
and then say, oh, I hear this
line, which happened just

00:44:48.970 --> 00:44:51.490
in a kind of random occurrence.

00:44:51.490 --> 00:44:53.440
I hear these couple
in notes be connected.

00:44:53.440 --> 00:44:55.780
I hear a melody happening there.

00:44:55.780 --> 00:44:57.280
Maybe I'll extract
that and connect

00:44:57.280 --> 00:44:58.750
those dots on a
single instrument,

00:44:58.750 --> 00:45:00.730
or something like this.

00:45:00.730 --> 00:45:02.470
There's not a kind
of computational way

00:45:02.470 --> 00:45:05.110
that I think about that.

00:45:05.110 --> 00:45:07.570
AUDIENCE: Have you ever
tried applying these methods

00:45:07.570 --> 00:45:11.530
to instruments that are
percussion or non-chromatic

00:45:11.530 --> 00:45:12.220
percussion?

00:45:12.220 --> 00:45:13.584
ELLIOT COLE: Yeah, definitely.

00:45:13.584 --> 00:45:15.000
I write a lot of
percussion music.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:16.420
Actually, I write
more percussion music

00:45:16.420 --> 00:45:17.230
than other music.

00:45:17.230 --> 00:45:18.860
And it's a great way--

00:45:18.860 --> 00:45:20.860
this also got me started
thinking about patterns

00:45:20.860 --> 00:45:22.780
and cycles in the
abstract, which

00:45:22.780 --> 00:45:25.220
is great for non-pitched music.

00:45:25.220 --> 00:45:27.850
So all I would need
to do is switch

00:45:27.850 --> 00:45:31.000
the instrument in my
virtual instruments

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:33.190
here to a percussion
instrument, and I

00:45:33.190 --> 00:45:36.340
would be exploring a totally
different kind of sonic space

00:45:36.340 --> 00:45:37.480
with the same ideas.

00:45:37.480 --> 00:45:39.160
Are you a percussionist?

00:45:39.160 --> 00:45:40.680
AUDIENCE: Yeah, that was one
of the first things I started,

00:45:40.680 --> 00:45:42.140
and I've moved to other things.

00:45:42.140 --> 00:45:44.350
But I just thought
of the example--

00:45:44.350 --> 00:45:46.532
we heard just the piano--

00:45:46.532 --> 00:45:49.820
you tried either
other keyboards,

00:45:49.820 --> 00:45:53.020
and I thought, well, why
keyboards, maybe just

00:45:53.020 --> 00:45:54.146
a non-chromatic percussion?

00:45:54.146 --> 00:45:55.564
ELLIOT COLE: It can be anything.

00:45:55.564 --> 00:45:56.730
This is just a little slice.

00:45:56.730 --> 00:45:57.688
AUDIENCE: Cool, thanks.

00:45:57.688 --> 00:45:58.960
ELLIOT COLE: Yeah thanks.

00:45:58.960 --> 00:46:00.580
Question?

00:46:00.580 --> 00:46:03.670
AUDIENCE: Can you talk
about how the values that we

00:46:03.670 --> 00:46:05.800
see in notes, velocity,
and time intervals

00:46:05.800 --> 00:46:08.020
correspond to what we
would see in a more

00:46:08.020 --> 00:46:10.436
traditional score, like how
you get from one to the other?

00:46:10.436 --> 00:46:11.860
ELLIOT COLE: Yes,
great question.

00:46:11.860 --> 00:46:16.390
I forget that this is
not a universal language.

00:46:16.390 --> 00:46:20.350
OK, so here, this
first bloom is 67.

00:46:20.350 --> 00:46:22.360
The first note is 67.

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:25.150
Note values are 0 to 127.

00:46:25.150 --> 00:46:28.870
67 happens to be G4.

00:46:28.870 --> 00:46:31.940
Velocities are also
values 0 to 127.

00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:39.260
And so you know, 61 is
a very moderate volume.

00:46:39.260 --> 00:46:41.380
And this is just in seconds--

00:46:41.380 --> 00:46:43.840
0.9 seconds.

00:46:43.840 --> 00:46:51.640
So high-low numbers in notes
is high and low on a score.

00:46:51.640 --> 00:46:57.310
And velocities, you know,
we have forte to piano.

00:46:57.310 --> 00:46:59.530
We have these kind of
traditional markings.

00:46:59.530 --> 00:47:02.860
And the hardest one to
represent is time intervals,

00:47:02.860 --> 00:47:07.450
because this is
just in raw seconds.

00:47:07.450 --> 00:47:10.330
It's not on any sort
of rhythmic grid.

00:47:10.330 --> 00:47:12.410
It's not in any kind of meter.

00:47:12.410 --> 00:47:15.430
And so from a score music
notation point of view,

00:47:15.430 --> 00:47:22.529
this is like outrageously
irresponsible and irrational

00:47:22.529 --> 00:47:24.070
to have all of these
numbers in here.

00:47:26.650 --> 00:47:30.730
But the biggest
struggle has been

00:47:30.730 --> 00:47:32.680
trying to represent
these rhythms on paper.

00:47:34.977 --> 00:47:37.310
AUDIENCE: You have a really
complicated line lower down.

00:47:40.390 --> 00:47:42.670
ELLIOT COLE: I remember.

00:47:42.670 --> 00:47:44.420
I practice that one.

00:47:44.420 --> 00:47:45.604
This one.

00:47:45.604 --> 00:47:46.500
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:47:46.500 --> 00:47:47.746
ELLIOT COLE: This?

00:47:47.746 --> 00:47:48.602
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
was wondering if you

00:47:48.602 --> 00:47:49.685
could explain [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:49.685 --> 00:47:52.219
ELLIOT COLE: Yeah, sure,
so this is a pattern

00:47:52.219 --> 00:47:54.010
that's reading through
one of those blooms,

00:47:54.010 --> 00:47:57.980
so reading through each
note of the list in order.

00:47:57.980 --> 00:48:04.510
And so I is which item of
the list it is reading.

00:48:08.140 --> 00:48:10.570
Let's see.

00:48:10.570 --> 00:48:11.580
We'll go inside out.

00:48:17.680 --> 00:48:22.240
This is just a series
from zero to infinity.

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:24.830
And it's going to
wrap around my loop.

00:48:24.830 --> 00:48:27.420
So this just represents going
through the list over and over

00:48:27.420 --> 00:48:27.920
again.

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:33.910
Again Pclump is a pattern that
is going to not just take one

00:48:33.910 --> 00:48:38.050
at a time, but take clumps at
a time and play them as chords.

00:48:38.050 --> 00:48:41.890
And how many it takes at
a time is this argument.

00:48:41.890 --> 00:48:44.062
And Pwhite is white noise.

00:48:44.062 --> 00:48:45.520
It's just a random
number generator

00:48:45.520 --> 00:48:46.690
between one and three.

00:48:46.690 --> 00:48:50.830
So I'm saying spin out this list
of all of my notes in a circle

00:48:50.830 --> 00:48:55.460
forever and grab either one
or two or three at a time.

00:48:55.460 --> 00:48:58.950
And so it's a random mix
of chords and single notes.

00:48:58.950 --> 00:49:00.950
Yeah, thanks.

00:49:00.950 --> 00:49:01.450
Thank you.

00:49:01.450 --> 00:49:04.500
[APPLAUSE]

